abe law. The author asks not only what these doodem markings indicate, but what they may also reveal through their exclusions. The book also ooutlines the continuities, changes, and innovations in Anishinaabe governance through the concept of council fires and the alliances between them. Original and path-breaking, Doodem and Council Fire offers a fresh approach to Indigenous history, presenting a new interpretation grounded in a deep understanding of the nuances and distinctiveness of Anishinaabe culture and Indigenous traditions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxHistory. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxPolitics and government. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxSocial life and customs. 0aOjibwa IndianszCanadaxPolitics and government. 7aLAW / Indigenous Peoples.2bisacsh  aAnishinaabe law.  aAnishinaabe.  aCanadian legal history.  aGreat Lakes.  aOjibwe.  aclan identification markings.  acouncil fire.  adoodem.  agovernance.  aindigenous law.  anatural history.  atreaty history.  atreaty pictographs.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266786040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442667860423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442667860.jpg  a978-3-11-069045-3  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles